\details{
This is an in-package, dependency-light analogue of \strong{time-varying parameter
(TVP) / state-space (dynamic linear) regression}: \verb{y_t = X_t b_t + e_t} with
\verb{b_t = b_\{t-1\} + w_t}. The dynamic simulator's random-window bootstrap
(\code{min_window} in \code{\link[=setup_system]{setup_system()}}) approximates the same object pointwise but
indexes it by a random window (start \emph{and} end), confounding recency with
sample size. \code{\link[=forecast_coefficients]{forecast_coefficients()}} instead uses a deterministic grid
anchored at the window \emph{end}, so the coefficient series is a clean function of
time that can be projected forward.

The forecast is deliberately the empirical/Gaussian version. The principled
estimators are state-space TVP models: \code{dlm} / \code{KFAS} (Kalman filter, no
MCMC), \code{shrinkTVP} / \code{walker} (Bayesian, with shrinkage toward a static
coefficient that guards against TVP overfitting), and \code{bvarsv} (TVP-VAR,
Primiceri 2005). Reach for those when you need filtered/smoothed states,
shrinkage, or formal posterior inference.

Bootstrap is forced off for the path fits (so each window yields the OLS/MLE
point estimate, not a single bootstrap realisation); the spec's own \code{boot}
setting is irrelevant here. The coefficient path is \strong{pooled across units},
matching the pooled \code{linear}/\code{glm} model. Only coefficient-bearing specs
(\code{linear}/\code{glm}) are forecast; others (including \code{heterolm}, which carries no
tidy coefficients) are skipped, mirroring \code{\link[=get_coefficients]{get_coefficients()}}.
}
